  "prompt": "What 6/9 mean in eyesight?",
  "response": "In the context of eyesight, the notation **6/9** is a way to express visual acuity, which measures how clearly a person can see from a specific distance. It is part of the **Snellen chart** system, commonly used by optometrists and ophthalmologists.\n\n- **6/9** means that you can see at **6 meters** what a person with normal vision can see at **9 meters**. \n- This indicates that your vision is slightly worse than \"normal\" vision, which is defined as **6/6**.\n\n### Breakdown:\n- **First number (6):** The distance at which the test is performed (6 meters, or about 20 feet).\n- **Second number (9):** The distance at which a person with normal vision could read the same line on the eye chart.\n\n### Interpretation:\n- **6/6** is considered normal vision.\n- **6/9** means you need to be closer (6 meters) to see what someone with normal vision can see at 9 meters. This suggests mild visual impairment, but it\u2019s not severe.\n\nIf your vision is worse than 6/9 (e.g., 6/12 or 6/18), it indicates greater difficulty seeing clearly, and you may need corrective lenses or other interventions. Always consult an eye care professional for a full assessment and advice.",
